[2] Outbreak/recall impact
Date: Mon 2 Feb 2009
Source: New York Daily News [edited]
<http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2009/02/02/2009-02-02_more_peanut_products_likely_recalled_ami.html>


Due to the salmonella outbreak, more recalls of peanut products are
expected this week, USA Today reported. There have already been more
than 800 recalls; this is one of the largest recalls ever. Last week
[26-30 Jan 2009], American health officials discovered that Peanut
Corp. of America, the likely source of the salmonella tainted peanut
products, went ahead and shipped peanut butter products despite
getting test results showing salmonella was present, Bloomberg News
reported last week.

The company's actions "can only be described as reprehensible and
criminal," Rep. Rosa DeLauro, who oversees Food and Drug
Administration funding, told USA Today. "Not only did this company
knowingly sell tainted products, it shopped for a laboratory that
would provide the acceptable results they were seeking. This behavior
represents the worst of our current food safety regulatory system."

Upon receivng the test results showing evidence of salmonella, Peanut
Corp. contacted other labs to conduct new tests, Michael Rogers,
director of the division of field investigations of the FDA, told
Bloomberg News. Rogers said "there were no steps taken" by the
company to reduce the presence of salmonella.

The salmonella outbreak has caused numerous product recalls including
recalls of products containing peanut butter from companies like
Kellogg, Little Debbie, Starbucks and others. USA Today reported that
Robert Brackett, senior vice president of the Grocery Manufacturers
Association, said he fears that the recall will affect demand in a
big way as consumers get sick of checking recall lists and simply
stop buying peanuts.

[Byline: Catey Hill]

