*****
[6] Japanese recall
Date: Mon 2 Feb 2009
Source: Mainichi Daily News [edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20090202p2a00m0na006000c.html>


Popcorn using the same peanut butter that caused a salmonella
outbreak in the USA was distributed in Japan in 2008, it has been
learned. The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare said on Saturday
[31 Jan 2009] that it has ordered Suzusho, the importer of the
popcorn in Tokyo's Shinjuku-ku, to suspend sales of the product and
to conduct a voluntary recall. It's not known if the product contains
bacteria, but no health damage has been reported so far.

According to the ministry, Suzusho imported a total of 437 cases
(about 545 kilograms) of the popcorn in July and August 2008. The
company recalled only 25 cases (31 kilograms), which were kept in
storage, and the rest had already been distributed to retailers via
wholesalers based mainly in the Kanto region. The ministry is also
ordering the distributors to investigate the matter, and is calling
for consumers to return the product.

